    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1523728677" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1523728677" />
    <a title="PattyMacDotComma" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1128612-pattymacdotcomma"><img alt="PattyMacDotComma" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1577835191p2/1128612.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1523728677?book_show_action=true">Oct 27, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="PattyMacDotComma" class="user" itemprop="url" name="PattyMacDotComma" href="/user/show/1128612-pattymacdotcomma">PattyMacDotComma</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780552160964" href="/book/show/18395043-i-am-pilgrim">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1128612-pattymacdotcomma?shelf=mystery-crime-thriller">mystery-crime-thriller</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1128612-pattymacdotcomma?shelf=audio">audio</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1128612-pattymacdotcomma?shelf=australian-author">australian-author</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1128612-pattymacdotcomma?shelf=chcc-library">chcc-library</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1128612-pattymacdotcomma?shelf=award-win-listed">award-win-listed</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1128612-pattymacdotcomma?shelf=dnf-abandoned">dnf-abandoned</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1523728677" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4051262873887262537"><b>3★<br/>“Due to my former work, I had more enemies than I cared to think about and I didn’t want to start my car engine one morning and end up as a handful of cosmic dust running rings around the moon.”</b><br/><br/>I should have liked this book. I should have enjoyed the plot and the characters. And I did, for a while. I began with the audio but started speeding it up as it seemed to be dragging. There were also some grisly details about killings and forensic investigation.<br/><br/>So I switched to reading a library versio</span>
  <span id="freeText4051262873887262537" style="display:none"><b>3★<br />“Due to my former work, I had more enemies than I cared to think about and I didn’t want to start my car engine one morning and end up as a handful of cosmic dust running rings around the moon.”</b><br /><br />I should have liked this book. I should have enjoyed the plot and the characters. And I did, for a while. I began with the audio but started speeding it up as it seemed to be dragging. There were also some grisly details about killings and forensic investigation.<br /><br />So I switched to reading a library version available for only an hour at a time online (and that was enough). At least I could pace myself and skim some of the worst stuff. In the beginning, I liked the main character and the story, how he was recruited into an elite government agency <b>“which worked so deep in shadow that only a handful of people knew of our existence . . .established by Jack Kennedy in the early months of his administration”.</b><br /><br />He begins as so many lone wolves do, as an only child whose father walked out before he was born and whose mother was murdered. Well, they don’t all have murdered mothers, but a lot of them are orphaned young. He was adopted by a wealthy couple and had the best of everything, except that the Mrs didn’t want him.<br /><br />We see him track down a powerful family of drug-dealers and arrange a hit. Later, the story turns to a young Saudi boy whose father has been beheaded in another gruesome episode. At one point, our main character says. <b>“Though no one will ever know for sure, I imagine that – mentally – he was being torn in two. . . ”</b> “He” is now referred to as the Saracen.<br /><br />I don’t know exactly where I noticed that the point of view was changing. Sometimes, the main character is narrating in the first person, sometimes it’s third person omniscient, where you have an outside storyteller, and then it goes back to our first person’s observations of what he thinks is happening.<br /><br />Our narrator, the main character, says again, that <b>“having seen all the secret evidence and, as I mentioned earlier, knowing more about him than anyone on earth, I am probably in the best position to say what happened up in the high mountains – an area which, despite the Saracen’s constant prayer rituals, must have given an entirely new meaning to the germ <i>‘godforsaken’.</i> <br /><br />Even though the tribesmen had mufflled their ponies well, the Saracen knew that they were there. Four days earlier, he had arrived and set up camp in the observation post’s old bunkhouse, blasted deep into the rock, and it was inside the cave that he awoke with a start. It was either his battlefield intuition or the restless movement of his horses that told him that he was no longer alone on the mountain.”</b><br /><br />So many people have loved this book, that I kept telling myself to just go along for the ride and enjoy the story. I gave up on the audio, although the narrator was fine – no complaints there. I just didn’t want some of those scenes echoing in my head quite so strongly.<br /><br />After about a third of the way through, I completely lost interest. I could see what the Saracen intended, but I couldn’t get past the fact that somehow I was privy to his innermost thoughts although I think I’m being told the story by the main character. It took me that much of the book to realise what my problem was, and it is obviously only my problem, or it wouldn’t be so popular, particularly for such a long read.<br /><br />So I apologise to all mystery lovers for my lack of enthusiasm, but maybe this was the wrong choice for right now. <br /><br />Moving right along . . .</span>
  <a data-text-id="4051262873887262537" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


